    <details>
      <summary>NOSE &amp; PARANASAL SINUSES:</summary>
      <h4>NOSE &amp; PARANASAL SINUSES:</h4>
      <p><strong>INSPECTION:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>External Nose:
          <ul>
            <li>Nasal pyramid: [e.g., Normal, Deviated, Saddle nose, Hump]</li>
            <li>Any deformity: [Describe]</li>
            <li>Skin over nose: [e.g., Normal, Redness, Swelling, Scars]</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Vestibule:
          <ul>
            <li>Any vestibulitis: [Yes/No]</li>
            <li>Hair follicle infection: [Yes/No] </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Nasal Cavity (on lifting the tip of the nose):
          <ul>
            <li>Caudal dislocation or deviation of septum: [Yes/No]</li>
            <li>Condition of the nasal mucosa: [e.g., Pink, Congested, Pale,
              Atrophic, Crusting]</li>
            <li>Any discharge: [e.g., Mucoid, Purulent, Bloody, Clear;
              Unilateral/Bilateral]</li>
            <li>Deviated Nasal Septum (DNS) or spur visible anteriorly: [Yes/No,
              Side, Type]</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>FUNCTIONAL TESTS &amp; ANTERIOR RHINOSCOPY:</strong></p>
      <ol>
        <li>Cold Spatula Test:
          <ul>
            <li>Using cold Lack&acirc;&euro;&trade;s tongue depressor, checked
              for decreased/absent fogging due to nasal obstruction.</li>
            <li>Right: [Fogging present/absent/reduced]</li>
            <li>Left: [Fogging present/absent/reduced]</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Anterior Rhinoscopy (Using Thudicum nasal speculum):
          <ul>
            <li>Nasal Septum: [e.g., Central, Deviated (to R/L,
              C-shaped/S-shaped), Spur, Perforation, Hematoma, Abscess]</li>
            <li>Turbinates (Inferior, Middle):
              <ul>
                <li>Right: [e.g., Normal
                  size/Hypertrophied/Atrophied/Congested/Pale]</li>
                <li>Left: [e.g., Normal
                  size/Hypertrophied/Atrophied/Congested/Pale]</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Mucosa:
              <ul>
                <li>Right: [e.g., Color, Congestion, Edema]</li>
                <li>Left: [e.g., Color, Congestion, Edema]</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Meatuses (Inferior, Middle):
              <ul>
                <li>Right: [e.g., Clear, Discharge (nature), Polyp]</li>
                <li>Left: [e.g., Clear, Discharge (nature), Polyp]</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Any synechiae, polyp, or mass: [Describe location, appearance if
              present]</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Probing (if mass present):
          <ul>
            <li>Mobility: [Yes/No]</li>
            <li>Sensitivity: [Tender/Non-tender]</li>
            <li>Bleeding on touch: [Yes/No]</li>
            <li>Consistency: [e.g., Soft, Firm, Hard, Friable]</li>
            <li>Able to go around mass or not: [Yes/No]</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ol>
      <p><strong>POSTERIOR RHINOSCOPY (Using warmed St. Claire Thompson mirror
          and Lack&acirc;&euro;&trade;s tongue depressor):</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Choanae: [Patent/Obstructed R/L]</li>
        <li>Posterior end of turbinates: [Normal/Hypertrophied/Congested R/L]</li>
        <li>Posterior end of septum: [Normal/Deviated]</li>
        <li>Eustachian tube openings: [Visible/Not visible]</li>
        <li>Fossa of Rosenmuller: [Clear/Fullness R/L]</li>
        <li>Any polyp or mass (e.g., adenoids, antrochoanal polyp): [Describe if
          present]</li>
      </ul>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>THROAT (ORAL CAVITY &amp; PHARYNX &amp; LARYNX):</summary>
      <h4>THROAT (ORAL CAVITY &amp; PHARYNX &amp; LARYNX):</h4>
      <p><strong>Using Lack&acirc;&euro;&trade;s tongue depressor,</strong></p>
      <p><strong>On Inspection:</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Lips: [e.g., Color, Symmetry, Swelling, Fissures, Cheilitis,
          Stomatitis, Herpes infection, Pigmentation]</li>
        <li>Mucosa of vestibule (inner lips and cheeks): [e.g., Color
          (pink/pale/congested), Aphthous ulcers, Lesions]</li>
        <li>Gingiva: [e.g., Color, Swelling, Bleeding, Gingivitis, Hypertrophy]</li>
        <li>Teeth: [Number, Caries, Stains, Malocclusion, Missing teeth, Dental
          hygiene]</li>
        <li>Buccal Mucosa: [e.g., Color (pink/pale/congested), Aphthous ulcers,
          Leukoplakia, Erythroplakia, Stensen's duct opening]</li>
        <li>Tongue:
          <ul>
            <li>Dorsum (tip, margins, surface): [e.g., Color, Texture, Coating,
              Papillae, Fissures, Glossitis, Ulcers, Deviation on protrusion]</li>
            <li>Ventral surface: [e.g., Frenulum (tongue-tie), Varicosities,
              Wharton's duct openings]</li>
            <li>Mobility: [Normal/Restricted]</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Floor of oral cavity: [e.g., Swelling, Ranula, Retention cyst, Signs
          of submandibular sialadenitis]</li>
        <li>Hard palate: [e.g., Arch (high/normal), Cleft, Torus palatinus,
          Fibrosis, Ulcers]</li>
        <li>Soft palate: [e.g., Symmetry, Movement on phonation ("say Aah"),
          Congestion, Lesions]</li>
        <li>Uvula: [e.g., Central/Deviated, Edematous, Bifid, Movement on
          phonation]</li>
        <li>Anterior pillars, Tonsillar fossa, Posterior pillars:
          <ul>
            <li>Tonsils (Palatine): [Present/Absent (tonsillectomy), Size (Grade
              0-4), Color (pink/congested), Crypts (debris/pus), Membrane,
              Asymmetry, Ervin Moore sign (bulging of anterior pillar)]</li>
            <li>Pillars: [Congestion, Swelling]</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Posterior pharyngeal wall: [e.g., Color, Cobblestoning,
          Granulations, Postnasal drip, Membranes, Bulge]</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>Indirect Laryngoscopy (IDL - Using warmed mirror, if age and
          cooperation permit):</strong></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Base of tongue &amp; Valleculae: [Normal, Pooling of saliva, Mass]</li>
        <li>Epiglottis: [Shape, Color, Edema]</li>
        <li>Aryepiglottic folds &amp; Arytenoids: [Symmetry, Edema, Movement]</li>
        <li>Pyriform fossae: [Clear, Pooling of saliva, Mass]</li>
        <li>Vocal Cords:
          <ul>
            <li>Appearance: [Color (pearly white/congested), Edge
              (smooth/irregular), Nodules, Polyps, Ulcers]</li>
            <li>Movement: [Symmetrical abduction on inspiration and adduction on
              phonation/Restricted movement (specify side and type of palsy)]</li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Subglottic region (if visible): [Normal, Swelling]</li>
        <li>Any growths or masses, any palsy etc.: [Describe]</li>
      </ul>
      <p><strong>On Palpation (Neck &amp; Oral Cavity as indicated):</strong></p>
    </details>
    <br>
    <h2> Systemic Examination:</h2>
    <br>
    <div> CNS<br>
      Higher functions, cranial nerves, sensory and motor<br>
      <br>
      CVS<br>
      Heart sounds, Murmurs<br>
      <br>
      Respiratory<br>
      Bilateral Air Entry, Type of Breath sounds<br>
      <br>
      GIT<br>
      Palpation of Abdomen</div>
    <br>
    <p><br>
    </p>
    <p><br>
    </p>
    <p><br>
    </p>
    <h3>DIAGNOSIS :</h3>
    <ol>
      <li>ANATOMICAL</li>
      <li>ETIOLOGICAL</li>
      <li>PATHOLOGICAL</li>
      <li>CLINICAL</li>
    </ol>
    <h4>Urgency</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Urgent Admission: </li>
      <li>Urgent Referral (2 weeks): </li>
      <li>Routine Referral: </li>
      <li>Handling In-House: </li>
    </ul>
    <ul>
      <li>Initial Investigations
        <ul>
          <li>Blood work: <em>Usually not required unless systemically unwell
              or suspected complication (e.g., FBC, CRP if mastoiditis
              suspected).</em></li>
          <li>Imaging: <em>Usually not required unless complications suspected
              (e.g., CT scan for mastoiditis or intracranial spread).</em></li>
          <li>Other:
            <ul>
              <li>Otoscopy: <em>(Key for diagnosis - bulging, red, immobile
                  tympanic membrane; possible perforation with discharge).</em></li>
              <li>Tympanometry: <em>(May show Type B or C curve, useful if
                  diagnosis uncertain or to assess for OME).</em></li>
            </ul>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Patient Communication
        <ul>
          <li><b>ICE</b>: <em>Explore patient/parent's Ideas (e.g., "Is it a
              bad infection?"), Concerns ("Will it affect hearing long-term?",
              "Does my child need antibiotics?"), Expectations ("I want
              something to stop the pain quickly.").</em></li>
          <li>Diagnosis disclosure: <em>Explain AOM, likely viral in many
              cases, often self-limiting.</em></li>
          <li>Explanation of findings: <em>Describe otoscopy findings simply.</em></li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Further Investigations
        <ul>
          <li>Specialized tests: <em>Audiometry if hearing concerns persist
              post-resolution or with recurrent AOM.</em></li>
          <li>Referrals: <em>ENT referral if: recurrent AOM (e.g., 3+ in 6
              months, 4+ in 12 months), persistent OME post-AOM, complications
              suspected, diagnostic uncertainty.</em></li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Treatment Plan
        <ul>
          <li>Symptomatic treatment:
            <ul>
              <li><b>Analgesia</b>:</li>
              <li>Paracetamol fever or </li>
              <li>Ibuprofen pain </li>
              <li>Anti emetics</li>
              <li>prochlorperazine</li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>Specific treatment: <em>(Based on NICE CG69 - Otitis Media
              (Acute))</em></li>
          <li>Non-Medical:
            <ol>
              <li>Watchful waiting/Safety netting: <em>Advise that symptoms
                  usually resolve in 3 days; provide "delayed/back-up
                  prescription" for antibiotics in some cases.</em></li>
              <li>Warm compress to the ear may provide comfort.</li>
              <li>Encourage fluid intake.</li>
            </ol>
          </li>
          <li>Medical:
            <ul>
              <li>Analgesia (as above).</li>
              <li>Antibiotics (e.g., Amoxicillin first-line, or Clarithromycin
                if penicillin allergy):
                <ul>
                  <li>Consider immediate antibiotics if: systemically unwell,
                    symptoms of serious illness, high risk of complications
                    (e.g., immunosuppression, significant comorbidities), child
                    &lt;2 years with bilateral AOM, or child with otorrhoea due
                    to AOM.</li>
                  <li>Consider delayed prescription if not meeting immediate
                    criteria but at risk of worsening.</li>
                </ul>
              </li>
              <li>Decongestants/Antihistamines: <em>Not recommended by NICE for
                  AOM.</em></li>
            </ul>
          </li>
          <li>Surgical: <em>Myringotomy with or without grommet insertion for
              recurrent AOM meeting specific criteria (not for uncomplicated
              acute episode).</em></li>
          <li>Admission required: <em>Rarely. Yes if: suspected serious
              complication (e.g., mastoiditis, meningitis, facial palsy),
              systemically very unwell, unable to manage oral intake/medication.</em></li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Follow Up
        <ul>
          <li>Frequency: <em>Review if symptoms worsen or do not improve within
              2-3 days (if on watchful waiting) or after completing antibiotics.
              Follow-up for hearing check if OME suspected post-AOM.</em></li>
          <li>Specialist referrals: <em>As above (ENT).</em></li>
          <li>Allied health: <em>Speech and language therapy if prolonged OME
              impacts development.</em></li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li>Patient Education
        <ul>
          <li>Warning Signs/Red Flags: <em>Worsening pain despite analgesia,
              new swelling/redness behind ear, facial weakness, high fever,
              stiff neck, lethargy, persistent vomiting.</em></li>
          <li>Educational materials provided: <em>Leaflet on AOM, managing
              fever, pain relief.</em></li>
          <li>Useful resources/links: <em>NHS website information on AOM.</em></li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <h2>Patient-Specific Plan </h2>
      <hr>
      <h3>1. Acute Otitis Media (AOM)</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Initial Investigations
          <ul>
            <li>Blood work: <em>Usually not required unless systemically unwell
                or suspected complication (e.g., FBC, CRP if mastoiditis
                suspected).</em></li>
            <li>Imaging: <em>Usually not required unless complications
                suspected (e.g., CT scan for mastoiditis or intracranial
                spread).</em></li>
            <li>Other:
              <ul>
                <li>Otoscopy: <em>(Key for diagnosis - bulging, red, immobile
                    tympanic membrane; possible perforation with discharge).</em></li>
                <li>Tympanometry: <em>(May show Type B or C curve, useful if
                    diagnosis uncertain or to assess for OME).</em></li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Patient Communication
          <ul>
            <li><b>ICE</b>: <em>Explore patient/parent's Ideas (e.g., "Is it a
                bad infection?"), Concerns ("Will it affect hearing long-term?",
                "Does my child need antibiotics?"), Expectations ("I want
                something to stop the pain quickly.").</em></li>
            <li>Diagnosis disclosure: <em>Explain AOM, likely viral in many
                cases, often self-limiting.</em></li>
            <li>Explanation of findings: <em>Describe otoscopy findings simply.</em></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Further Investigations
          <ul>
            <li>Specialized tests: <em>Audiometry if hearing concerns persist
                post-resolution or with recurrent AOM.</em></li>
            <li>Referrals: <em>ENT referral if: recurrent AOM (e.g., 3+ in 6
                months, 4+ in 12 months), persistent OME post-AOM, complications
                suspected, diagnostic uncertainty.</em></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Treatment Plan
          <ul>
            <li>Symptomatic treatment:
              <ul>
                <li>Analgesia: Paracetamol or Ibuprofen for pain and fever (dose
                  according to age/weight).</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Specific treatment: <em>(Based on NICE CG69 - Otitis Media
                (Acute))</em></li>
            <li>Non-Medical:
              <ol>
                <li>Watchful waiting/Safety netting: <em>Advise that symptoms
                    usually resolve in 3 days; provide "delayed/back-up
                    prescription" for antibiotics in some cases.</em></li>
                <li>Warm compress to the ear may provide comfort.</li>
                <li>Encourage fluid intake.</li>
              </ol>
            </li>
            <li>Medical:
              <ul>
                <li>Analgesia (as above).</li>
                <li>Antibiotics (e.g., Amoxicillin first-line, or Clarithromycin
                  if penicillin allergy):
                  <ul>
                    <li>Consider immediate antibiotics if: systemically unwell,
                      symptoms of serious illness, high risk of complications
                      (e.g., immunosuppression, significant comorbidities),
                      child &lt;2 years with bilateral AOM, or child with
                      otorrhoea due to AOM.</li>
                    <li>Consider delayed prescription if not meeting immediate
                      criteria but at risk of worsening.</li>
                  </ul>
                </li>
                <li>Decongestants/Antihistamines: <em>Not recommended by NICE
                    for AOM.</em></li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Surgical: <em>Myringotomy with or without grommet insertion for
                recurrent AOM meeting specific criteria (not for uncomplicated
                acute episode).</em></li>
            <li>Admission required: <em>Rarely. Yes if: suspected serious
                complication (e.g., mastoiditis, meningitis, facial palsy),
                systemically very unwell, unable to manage oral
                intake/medication.</em></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Follow Up
          <ul>
            <li>Frequency: <em>Review if symptoms worsen or do not improve
                within 2-3 days (if on watchful waiting) or after completing
                antibiotics. Follow-up for hearing check if OME suspected
                post-AOM.</em></li>
            <li>Specialist referrals: <em>As above (ENT).</em></li>
            <li>Allied health: <em>Speech and language therapy if prolonged OME
                impacts development.</em></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Patient Education
          <ul>
            <li>Warning Signs/Red Flags: <em>Worsening pain despite analgesia,
                new swelling/redness behind ear, facial weakness, high fever,
                stiff neck, lethargy, persistent vomiting.</em></li>
            <li>Educational materials provided: <em>Leaflet on AOM, managing
                fever, pain relief.</em></li>
            <li>Useful resources/links: <em>NHS website information on AOM.</em></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ol>
      <hr>
      <h3>2. Otitis Externa (OE)</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Initial Investigations
          <ul>
            <li>Blood work: <em>Usually not required unless systemically unwell
                or suspected malignant OE (e.g., FBC, ESR, CRP, Glucose in
                diabetics).</em></li>
            <li>Imaging: <em>Rarely. CT/MRI if malignant OE or complications
                suspected.</em></li>
            <li>Other:
              <ul>
                <li>Otoscopy: <em>(Key - inflamed, swollen ear canal, debris,
                    discharge; TM may be obscured or normal).</em></li>
                <li>Ear swab for MC&amp;S: <em>If recurrent, severe, not
                    responding to initial treatment, or in immunocompromised
                    patients.</em></li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Patient Communication
          <ul>
            <li><b>ICE</b>: <em>Ideas ("Is it an infection from swimming?"),
                Concerns ("Will it spread?", "How long until the pain stops?"),
                Expectations ("I need strong antibiotics.").</em></li>
            <li>Diagnosis disclosure: <em>Explain Otitis Externa
                (inflammation/infection of ear canal).</em></li>
            <li>Explanation of findings: <em>Describe otoscopy findings.</em></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Further Investigations
          <ul>
            <li>Specialized tests: <em>As above (swab).</em></li>
            <li>Referrals: <em>ENT referral if: severe OE, not responding to
                primary care treatment, suspected malignant OE, canal very
                swollen preventing drop administration (may need wick/aural
                toilet), diagnostic uncertainty.</em></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Treatment Plan
          <ul>
            <li>Symptomatic treatment:
              <ul>
                <li>Analgesia: Paracetamol, Ibuprofen. Codeine if severe pain.</li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Specific treatment: <em>(Based on NICE CKS - Otitis Externa)</em></li>
            <li>Non-Medical:
              <ol>
                <li>Keep ear dry: Avoid swimming, use earplugs or cotton wool
                  with petroleum jelly when showering/bathing.</li>
                <li>Avoid inserting anything into the ear canal (cotton buds,
                  fingers).</li>
                <li>Remove any hearing aids from affected ear until resolved.</li>
              </ol>
            </li>
            <li>Medical:
              <ul>
                <li>Topical Acetic Acid 2% spray/drops: <em>For mild OE.</em></li>
                <li>Topical antibiotic drops/spray: <em>(e.g., Ciprofloxacin,
                    Gentamicin, Neomycin-containing).</em></li>
                <li>Topical antibiotic with corticosteroid drops/spray: <em>Often
                    first-line for moderate/severe OE to reduce inflammation and
                    pain (e.g., Otomize, Gentisone HC).</em></li>
                <li>Aural toilet/microsuction: <em>By trained professional if
                    canal occluded by debris/swelling.</em></li>
                <li>Ear wick: <em>May be inserted by GP/ENT if canal very
                    swollen to help deliver drops.</em></li>
                <li>Oral antibiotics: <em>If infection spreading beyond ear
                    canal (cellulitis of pinna/face), systemic upset, or in
                    immunocompromised/diabetic patients with more severe OE.
                    Flucloxacillin or Clarithromycin.</em></li>
                <li>Antifungal drops: <em>If fungal infection suspected or
                    confirmed (otomycosis).</em></li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Surgical: <em>Rarely needed for uncomplicated OE. Incision
                &amp; drainage if abscess forms.</em></li>
            <li>Admission required: <em>Yes if: suspected malignant
                (necrotizing) otitis externa, severe cellulitis, systemically
                unwell requiring IV antibiotics.</em></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Follow Up
          <ul>
            <li>Frequency: <em>Review in 1 week if not improving or sooner if
                worsening. For malignant OE, close specialist follow-up.</em></li>
            <li>Specialist referrals: <em>ENT as above.</em></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Patient Education
          <ul>
            <li>Warning Signs/Red Flags: <em>Worsening pain despite treatment,
                spreading redness/swelling, facial weakness, persistent fever,
                discharge not improving.</em></li>
            <li>Educational materials provided: <em>Leaflet on Otitis Externa,
                how to apply ear drops correctly, water precautions.</em></li>
            <li>Useful resources/links: <em>NHS website.</em></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ol>
      <hr>
      <h3>3. Otitis Media with Effusion (OME / Glue Ear)</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Initial Investigations
          <ul>
            <li>Blood work: <em>Not applicable.</em></li>
            <li>Imaging: <em>Not applicable.</em></li>
            <li>Other:
              <ul>
                <li>Otoscopy: <em>(Dull, retracted tympanic membrane, air-fluid
                    levels or bubbles, yellowish/blueish discoloration).</em></li>
                <li>Tympanometry: <em>(Key - typically Type B curve indicating
                    middle ear fluid).</em></li>
                <li>Audiometry: <em>(To quantify conductive hearing loss).</em></li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Patient Communication
          <ul>
            <li><b>ICE</b>: <em>Ideas ("Is it an infection?", "Will it go away
                by itself?"), Concerns ("Will it affect my child's
                speech/schooling?"), Expectations ("Do they need grommets
                straight away?").</em></li>
            <li>Diagnosis disclosure: <em>Explain OME (fluid in middle ear
                without acute infection).</em></li>
            <li>Explanation of findings: <em>Show/explain otoscopy and
                tympanometry results.</em></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Further Investigations
          <ul>
            <li>Specialized tests: <em>Repeat audiometry and tympanometry after
                observation period.</em></li>
            <li>Referrals: <em>ENT referral if persistent OME (&gt;3 months)
                with significant hearing loss or impact on development/quality
                of life. Speech and Language Therapy assessment if concerns
                about development.</em></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Treatment Plan
          <ul>
            <li>Symptomatic treatment: <em>Manage any associated nasal
                congestion if relevant (though evidence for decongestants in OME
                is poor).</em></li>
            <li>Specific treatment: <em>(Based on NICE CG60 - Otitis Media with
                Effusion in under 12s)</em></li>
            <li>Non-Medical:
              <ol>
                <li>Active Observation ('Watchful Waiting'): <em>For 3 months
                    initially, as many cases resolve spontaneously.</em></li>
                <li>Autoinflation (e.g., Otovent device): <em>Consider for
                    children able to cooperate, during observation period.</em></li>
                <li>Educational support: <em>Advise on communication strategies
                    (face child, reduce background noise).</em></li>
              </ol>
            </li>
            <li>Medical:
              <ul>
                <li>Hearing Aids: <em>Consider if OME persistent and surgery
                    contraindicated or declined, or as an interim measure.</em></li>
                <li>Antibiotics/Steroids/Antihistamines/Decongestants: <em>Not
                    routinely recommended by NICE for managing OME.</em></li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Surgical:
              <ul>
                <li>Grommet (Ventilation Tube) Insertion: <em>Consider if
                    persistent bilateral OME for &ge;3 months AND hearing loss
                    in better ear &ge;25-30 dBHL, OR significant impact on
                    development/education/quality of life.</em></li>
                <li>Adenoidectomy: <em>Consider if nasal obstruction due to
                    adenoids and OME, or as part of grommet surgery in certain
                    cases.</em></li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Admission required: <em>No, surgery is typically a day-case
                procedure.</em></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Follow Up
          <ul>
            <li>Frequency: <em>After 3 months of active observation.
                Post-grommet insertion checks (e.g., 6 weeks, then as needed
                until extrusion).</em></li>
            <li>Specialist referrals: <em>ENT, Audiology, Speech and Language
                Therapy as indicated.</em></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Patient Education
          <ul>
            <li>Warning Signs/Red Flags: <em>Ear discharge post-grommets, signs
                of acute infection, worsening hearing.</em></li>
            <li>Educational materials provided: <em>Leaflet on OME, grommets,
                autoinflation.</em></li>
            <li>Useful resources/links: <em>National Deaf Children's Society
                (NDCS), NHS website.</em></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ol>
      <hr>
      <h3>4. Impacted Earwax (Cerumen Impaction)</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Initial Investigations
          <ul>
            <li>Blood work: <em>Not applicable.</em></li>
            <li>Imaging: <em>Not applicable.</em></li>
            <li>Other:
              <ul>
                <li>Otoscopy: <em>(To visualize wax and confirm impaction,
                    assess TM if visible).</em></li>
                <li>Tuning fork tests (Rinne/Weber): <em>May suggest conductive
                    loss if wax is occlusive.</em></li>
              </ul>
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Patient Communication
          <ul>
            <li><b>ICE</b>: <em>Ideas ("Do I need syringing?"), Concerns ("Is
                it damaging my hearing?"), Expectations ("I want it out now.").</em></li>
            <li>Diagnosis disclosure: <em>Explain impacted earwax.</em></li>
            <li>Explanation of findings: <em>Show otoscopy if possible, explain
                role of wax.</em></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Further Investigations
          <ul>
            <li>Specialized tests: <em>Audiometry if hearing loss persists
                after wax removal or if underlying sensorineural loss suspected.</em></li>
            <li>Referrals: <em>ENT or audiology clinic for microsuction or
                irrigation if primary care methods fail or are contraindicated.</em></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Treatment Plan
          <ul>
            <li>Symptomatic treatment: <em>Address any discomfort if present
                (rare).</em></li>
            <li>Specific treatment: <em>(Based on NICE CKS - Earwax)</em></li>
            <li>Non-Medical:
              <ol>
                <li>Advise against using cotton buds or other objects to clean
                  ear canal.</li>
              </ol>
            </li>
            <li>Medical:
              <ul>
                <li>Ear drops to soften wax: <em>Olive oil, almond oil, sodium
                    bicarbonate 5%, or urea hydrogen peroxide 5% drops for 3-5
                    days.</em></li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Procedural (if drops fail and wax is symptomatic/obscuring TM
              view):
              <ul>
                <li>Ear Irrigation (previously syringing): <em>With water at
                    body temperature, if no contraindications (e.g., TM
                    perforation, active infection).</em></li>
                <li>Microsuction: <em>Preferred method by many ENTs, especially
                    if irrigation contraindicated or previous problems.</em></li>
                <li>Manual removal: <em>Using instruments by a trained
                    professional.</em></li>
              </ul>
            </li>
            <li>Surgical: <em>Not applicable for simple wax.</em></li>
            <li>Admission required: <em>No.</em></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Follow Up
          <ul>
            <li>Frequency: <em>Usually not required unless symptoms persist
                after treatment or for recurrent impaction needing regular
                management.</em></li>
            <li>Specialist referrals: <em>As above.</em></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li>Patient Education
          <ul>
            <li>Warning Signs/Red Flags: <em>Pain, discharge, or worsening
                hearing after attempted removal &ndash; seek review.</em></li>
            <li>Educational materials provided: <em>Leaflet on earwax and safe
                ear care, how to use ear drops.</em></li>
            <li>Useful resources/links: <em>NHS website.</em></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ol>
      <!-- Add similar detailed sections for Tinnitus, SSNHL, BPPV, Meniere's, etc. following NICE if possible -->
      <hr>
      <p><em>Further conditions like Tinnitus, Sudden Sensorineural Hearing Loss
          (SSNHL), Benign Paroxysmal Positional Vertigo (BPPV), and Meniere's
          Disease would follow a similar structure, with investigations and
          treatments tailored to those specific NICE guidelines and clinical
          presentations. For example, SSNHL requires URGENT referral and
          consideration of steroids. BPPV involves diagnostic maneuvers
          (Dix-Hallpike) and treatment maneuvers (Epley). Tinnitus management
          focuses on coping and sound therapy.</em></p>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      1) CHRONIC SUPPURATIVE OTITIS MEDIA (CSOM)<br>
      <br>
      Chief Complaints:<br>
      <br>
      Mention chief complaints in patient&rsquo;s own words in chronological
      order with duration.<br>
      <br>
      Common:<br>
      Discharge from ear<br>
      Impairment in hearing<br>
      Pain in ear<br>
      Itching/Blocked sensation in ear<br>
      <br>
      Rare and due to complications:<br>
      Ringing sensation in ear<br>
      Dizziness<br>
      Feeling of fullness in ear<br>
      Swelling in mastoid/zygomatic region, etc.<br>
      Fever<br>
      Headache<br>
      Stiffness of neck<br>
      Inability to close eyelids<br>
      Facial asymmetry<br>
      Impairment of vision<br>
      <br>
      History of Present Illness:<br>
      <br>
      Apparently asymptomatic ____ time ago and then developed&hellip;.<br>
      <br>
      Ask about each complaint, its onset, duration, progression, aggravating,
      relieving factors, and<br>
      effect on taking medication.<br>
      <br>
      For discharge in addition ask color, amount, smell, type, consistency and
      any associated<br>
      condition.<br>
      <br>
      For impairment in hearing in addition ask if its uni or bilateral, if
      fluctuating, if autophony present,<br>
      etc.<br>
      <br>
      For pain in ear in addition ask about site, nature of pain, any radiation,
      any relevant history<br>
      suggesting it&rsquo;s referred, and any associations.<br>
      <br>
      For ringing sensation in addition ask type and nature.<br>
      <br>
      For dizziness/vertigo ask about any loss of consciousness.<br>
      <br>
      For fever ask about any evening rise, if associated with chills and rigors
      or not, etc.<br>
      <br>
      Ask about any recent ASOM, URTI and other focal infections etc.<br>
       Elicit any relevant positive and negative history to the complaints.<br>
      <br>
      Provisional Diagnosis:<br>
      <br>
      *Case Summary*and provisional diagnosis is: Chronic Suppurative Otitis
      Media<br>
      OF Right /Left /Both ear(s)<br>
      AND Tubotympanic/Atticoantral type<br>
      IN Active/ Quiescent/ Inactive/ Healed stage<br>
      WITH/WITHOUT Conductive deafness<br>
      WITH/WITHOUT Complications like _______________<br>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <br>
      2) SINONASAL POLYPOSIS (SNP)<br>
      <br>
      Chief Complaints:<br>
      <br>
      Mention chief complaints in patient&rsquo;s own words in chronological
      order with duration.<br>
      <br>
      Nasal obstruction<br>
      Nasal discharge<br>
      Bleeding through nose<br>
      Hawking sensation<br>
      Headache<br>
      Facial heaviness<br>
      Swelling or broadening of nose<br>
      Disturbance of smell<br>
      Snoring or sleep apnea<br>
      Change in tone of voice<br>
      Disturbance of taste<br>
      <br>
      History of Present Illness:<br>
      <br>
      Apparently asymptomatic ____ time ago and then developed&hellip;.<br>
      <br>
      Ask about each complaint, its onset, duration, progression, aggravating,
      relieving factors, and<br>
      effect on taking medication.<br>
      <br>
      For nasal obstruction ask about laterality, if alternating between two
      sides, more during<br>
      inspiration or expiration, if associated with taking topical drops.<br>
      <br>
      For discharge in addition ask color, amount, smell, type, consistency and
      any associated<br>
      condition.<br>
      <br>
      For sneezing asked if associated with certain surroundings, and if a lot
      of sneezes in short<br>
      duration.<br>
      <br>
      For Headache ask about laterality, if coming in bouts or continuous or
      diurnal variations etc.<br>
      <br>
      Elicit any relevant positive and negative history to the complaints.<br>
      Provisional Diagnosis:<br>
      <br>
      *Case Summary*and provisional diagnosis is: Unilateral/ Bilateral
      Sinonasal Polyposis<br>
      <br>
      Possibly Antrochoanal/ Ethmoidal polyp,<br>
      WITH/WITHOUT DNS towards right/ left side and caudal dislocation towards
      right/left side<br>
      WITH/WITHOUT Sinusitis<br>
      WITH/WITHOUT complications like ______________<br>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <p><br>
      </p>
      <br>
